occurrenceRemarks: A new population to me. Wooded roadside, west side of road, wet ditch, and plenty of poison ivy! In 120 linear feet there were 68 plants, growing on both banks of the ditch. 43 plants were flowering, 18 had been mowed, with their cut flower stems remaining above the leaves, and 7 plants had no signs of flowers. I had a really nice time counting and taking pictures.

informationWithheld: Coordinate uncertainty increased to 28762m to protect threatened taxon
occurrenceRemarks: Sloped roadside, rocky woodlands, utility right of way, two streams converge into one then go under the road via culvert. Walked 140 feet of length of 1 stream. Water had cut the clay soil deeply, so Heuchera was growing both at the top of the streambank, on the vertical walls of the streambank, and on higher soil around the culvert. I counted 29 plants, 6 with browsed flower stems, and 14 with blooms. There were almost 50 plants here in January and I am wondering what happened since then - the side of the stream closest to the roads was a thicket of Rubus and Lonicera japonica, so I wonder if a lot of plants were buried under that mess. January observation is here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/104124387

informationWithheld: Coordinate uncertainty increased to 28734m to protect threatened taxon
occurrenceRemarks: Roadside, slope above stream. Sadly, repairs to flooding damage of culvert and road appear to have brought in Japanese Knotweed. I counted 8 “clumps” of Heuchera caroliniana here, some already immersed in knotweed or multi flora rose. Checking the streambank on the other side of the road was impossible because the knotweed growth was thicker and taller there. Taking a few steps into the woods, I did see, from a distance, two Heuchera plants there, away from the knotweed, so that was hopeful. On another note, I was not impressed that all the old blacktop material from the road repair was just dumped on the slope. All the plants are doing their best to persevere.

informationWithheld: Coordinate uncertainty increased to 28734m to protect threatened taxon
occurrenceRemarks: This past winter, I counted at least 20 plants at this location, which is where an electric utility ROW with plenty of moist soil meets a roadside ditch. Each flower head shown is from a different plant in the colony. There were at least three plants whose flowers and leaves had been browsed. Others were in bud only, or had no buds or blooms at all. It was a steadily windy day and no pollinators were observed. @jameamoroso, an intersection with another road is close by and I want you to know that I did see plants on that roadside, too, but I was hangry, so I went home. 😁 Another day….

informationWithheld: Coordinate uncertainty increased to 28762m to protect threatened taxon
occurrenceRemarks: Roadside, relatively level area, rocky wooded edges, 3-4 foot wide stream with clay sides and rock bed. 19 plants growing on the lip, or very edge, of the stream bank, close to the water level. Two plants only just beginning to bloom, 3 budding, 4 showed browsed flower stems. The remainder had no flower buds at this time. Without actual measurements, the plants in this area were small, with no large, multi-plant clumps. Area examined included 156 linear feet of stream, both sides of the banks. I gotta say, I am amazed at how many plants of this species I am finding on roadsides!

occurrenceRemarks: Rocky woodland, roadside, sloped above a nearby stream (but not growing near the stream itself). All plants were on the south side of the road in a drainage ditch with standing water. The presence of lots of moss made it seem as if it is often this wet. I walked about 70 feet and counted 37 plants, a nice abundance, about half in bloom and bud, several others had browsed flower stems. Most of the plants here have leaves with some red coloration. Nice.

occurrenceRemarks: @ry_folk, this is the 4th population I know of. I have seen 30 individual plants here in the past, but Japanese honeysuckle, greenbriers and Virginia creeper have just made a horrible thicket. Today I only found 2 plants, one in the soil at the base of the tree and the other growing on the bark of the same tree’s roots. The roots were long ago exposed by flood waters of an intermittent stream. I love that the plant was growing and blooming without visible soil, suspended 4+ feet above the stream. Now I hope I find more populations...
